First off, the pour looked weak. I have come to expect a more viscous stream from this style and this was too transparent. The head was minimal and didn’t last. Good thing for you is I don’t care much about appearance that much. I might have given a 4/5 if it had more head, some retention and residual lacing. Upon first sniff, I get coffee and a general roastiness. On the second, I think I get some lactose or milk chocolate. By not providing a product description on the label, I am kind of experiencing a blind tasting of sorts in that I am not duping myself in detecting what the label tells me should be in here. The sip: I am usually describing new or emphasizing on previous flavors, but the body was more noticeable. As I would expect with a weak pour, I get a thinner body than I would expect from the style and the sip ends with some cloying but nothing negative. For an 8.2% ABV beverage, this is damn easy to drink. It’s a bit simple in its flavor, but this is definitely within the parameters of the style. I would have preferred a little more (dark or milk) chocolate in this to make the flavor last longer. It’s a good R.I.S. and I must take into consideration where this was brewed and bottled: Moerlein. I respect Moerlein and have had over 50 beers from there of which I have preferred the seasonal and limited series releases. I’m trying to find something unique about this example I cannot: no gimmicks, no hype, a straight up impy stout with a neat label. I went with a 15 overall because the 8.2% ABV is well hidden. The aroma was good, but nothing complex. The taste was sweet but not annoyingly so. Palate improved as it got warmer. Without knowing what the vision for beer is, I think this was a great value $7.99 for 22oz, but I think I will pass next time I see it unless the value is even better. I would recommend this to people who want to try something stronger but are afraid of having something that overwhelming in taste or aroma. Who knows, this might be a gateway beer to bigger and wilder things? In case the brewer(s) is/are reading this. I hope I have given the kind of feedback you can use without sounding too critical. I like craft beer and fear I have become too eager to have the next crazy, over-the-top concoction, to notice the good beer that this was. Thank you. ---second pour: I got more head and better retention this time. will boost appearance score to reflect this.'}, {'beer_name': 'Beautiful View IPA', 'beer_score': '3.2', 'review_date': 'Friday, August 19, 2016', 'review_text': 'Appearance: Light amber. The 90 year old bought the name and contract brews in in Memphis. The original brewery was damaged and looted after Katrina. This tastes refreshing and crisp, and just feels good to see that label again, facilitating imaginary time travel. I hope they make it the go to cheap beer and displace PBR in the city. I’m sure both hipsters and the old timers they are replacing can appreciate it equally. Maybe it will be the neutral/common ground between these opposing demographics.
